Architecture Decision Document (ADD): Hybrid API Routing & Integration Patterns
Context Understanding The enterprise operates a hybrid-cloud topology comprising Public Cloud (Region West/East) and On-Premises Datacenters (Primary/DR). As part of our API-led modernization and Open Banking initiatives, we must standardize how traffic traverses physical security boundaries to ensure auditability, mitigate operational drift, and protect legacy Systems of Record (Mainframe/Core Banking) from synchronous overload.
Key Assumptions
	•	Network Backbone: AWS Direct Connect / Azure ExpressRoute provides highly available, private transit between Cloud and On-Prem. MPLS/SD-WAN connects the datacenters.
	•	Identity: Public Cloud uses modern OAuth2/OIDC (JWTs). Legacy Core systems require mTLS, basic auth, or legacy mainframe tokens (e.g., RACF).
	•	Zero Trust: We assume the internal network is "hostile." Cross-boundary traffic must be authenticated and authorized.
Use Case 1: External Partner (B2B) Calls Data Center
Scenario: A fintech partner or corporate client consumes an Open Banking API (e.g., Payment Initiation or Account Information) hosted on-premises.
	•	Option A: Dedicated Partner Gateway (On-Prem DMZ). Partners connect directly to an on-premises B2B API Gateway via dedicated IPsec tunnels or public IPs exposed via the physical DMZ.
	◦	Pros: Direct path, completely isolates B2B traffic from public consumer traffic.
	◦	Cons: Requires exposing on-prem IPs to the internet; lacks cloud-scale DDoS elasticity; duplicates WAF management.
	•	Option B: Unified Cloud Edge Transit. Partners connect via the Public Cloud Edge (GSLB → Cloud WAF →Cloud API GW), which then securely proxies the request down the Direct Connect line to the DC Ingress Gateway.
	◦	Pros: Consolidates all internet-facing attack surfaces in the public cloud. Leverages elastic WAF and DDoS protection.
	◦	Cons: Adds a routing hop; requires managing B2B MTLS certificates at the Cloud API Gateway.
Recommendation: Option B (Unified Cloud Edge Transit). > Rationale: In a modern banking architecture, the on-premises datacenter should ideally have zero inbound internet exposure. By routing Open Banking and B2B partners through the Cloud API Gateway, we standardize edge security policies (rate limiting, IP allowlisting, OAuth validation). The Cloud API Gateway acts as the public front door, and the DC Ingress Gateway acts as the internal border control (token translation, ingress policy). Traversal Path:External Partner → Cloud WAF → Cloud API GW → DC Ingress Gateway → Domain API GW → Core.
Use Case 2: Cross-Datacenter Routing (East-West between DCs)
Scenario: A Microservice in DC-West needs to synchronously call a Domain API hosted exclusively in DC-East (e.g., calling a centralized Risk Scoring engine).
	•	Option A: Direct Domain-to-Domain. The microservice in DC-West calls the Domain API Gateway in DC-East directly over the MPLS WAN.
	◦	Pros: Lowest latency; simple to set up initially.
	◦	Cons: Punches point-to-point firewall holes across datacenters. Creates a "mesh" of unmanageable firewall rules over time.
	•	Option B: Transit via DC Ingress Gateways. The request routes from DC-West App Layer → DC-East Ingress Gateway → DC-East Domain API Gateway.
	◦	Pros: Single point of ingress for the destination datacenter. Strict network segmentation. Centralized cross-site logging.
	◦	Cons: Slight latency increase (approx. 5-10ms) due to the perimeter inspection.
Recommendation: Option B (Transit via DC Ingress Gateways). > Rationale: We must prevent "firewall Swiss cheese." Treating DC-East as a distinct security zone relative to DC-West ensures that a compromise or lateral movement in one datacenter is caught at the perimeter of the other. The DC Ingress Gateway serves as the centralized enforcement point for cross-site mTLS and rate limits, protecting the target domain from "friendly fire" DDoS if the calling domain scales out aggressively. Traversal Path: DC West Domain →Internal LB → MPLS WAN → DC East Ingress Gateway → DC East Domain GW.
Use Case 3: Hybrid Cloud Routing (Cloud K8s to On-Prem)
Scenario: A cloud-native digital channel microservice (e.g., Mobile App BFF in Azure/AWS) must fetch customer ledger balances from the on-prem Mainframe.
	•	Option A: Direct to Domain Gateway. Cloud Microservice calls the On-Prem Domain API Gateway directly over Direct Connect.
	◦	Cons: Exposes internal domain network topology to the cloud. Forces the Domain Gateway to handle external token translation (JWT to internal token).
	•	Option B: Cloud Internal Gateway to DC Ingress. Cloud Microservice routes to a dedicated "Egress" API Gateway in the cloud, which then connects to the DC Ingress Gateway.
	◦	Cons: Introduces unnecessary proxy hops ("layer cake" anti-pattern). Over-engineers the cloud side.
	•	Option C: Direct to DC Ingress Gateway. Cloud Microservice calls the physical DC Ingress Gateway over Direct Connect, which translates the request and proxies it to the Domain Gateway.
	◦	Pros: Balances performance with security. Keeps the cloud lightweight while enforcing strict Border Control at the physical datacenter edge.
Recommendation: Option C (Direct to DC Ingress Gateway). Rationale: As agreed in our prior review, this honors the "Border Control" pattern without succumbing to business API chaining. The DC Ingress Gateway validates the cloud identity (JWT), exchanges it for the required internal legacy identity (e.g., RACF/mTLS), and performs content-agnostic routing to the Domain Gateway. The Domain Gateway handles the domain-specific business logic and integration with the System of Record. Traversal Path: Cloud Microservice → Direct Connect → DC Ingress Gateway → Domain Gateway → Core Banking.

