Use Case 4: Intra-Datacenter Routing (East-West within the same DC)
Scenario: A microservice in the 'Digital Channels' domain (e.g., Mobile BFF) needs to synchronously call a service in the 'Payments' domain (e.g., Payment Execution) residing in the same datacenter.
	•	Option A: Hairpinning through DC Ingress Gateway. Traffic leaves the Digital Channels domain, routes up to the DC Ingress Gateway (Border Control), and is proxied back down to the Payments Domain Gateway.
	◦	Pros: Centralized visibility of all internal traffic.
	◦	Cons: Severe Anti-Pattern. Creates a massive centralized bottleneck (the "ESB" trap). Introduces unnecessary latency ("tromboning" or "hairpinning") and couples internal domain availability to perimeter hardware.
	•	Option B: Direct Point-to-Point. Services call each other directly, bypassing gateways.
	◦	Pros: Zero routing latency.
	◦	Cons: Spaghettification. No localized rate-limiting, no domain-level isolation, and completely decentralized trust.
	•	Option C: Domain-to-Domain via Domain API Gateways (or Service Mesh). The Digital Channels Domain Gateway routes directly to the Payments Domain Gateway over the internal data center switching fabric.
	◦	Pros: Enforces Domain-Driven Design (DDD) boundaries. Allows domains to set their own rate limits and internal SLAs. Prevents a localized domain failure from impacting the global perimeter.
Recommendation: Option C (Domain-to-Domain via Domain API Gateways). Rationale: In a banking environment, we must compartmentalize blast radii. By routing East-West traffic exclusively through Domain Gateways (or an internal Service Mesh if running Kubernetes on-prem), we decouple internal transaction velocity from the perimeter. The DC Ingress Gateway must be reserved strictly for crossing physical security trust zones (Cloud to On-Prem, Partner to On-Prem, DC to DC). Traversal Path: Originating Domain Component → Originating Domain GW → Internal Network → Target Domain GW → Target Component.
Use Case 5: South-North Egress (Legacy On-Prem to Cloud/External)
Scenario: A Mainframe batch process or on-premises Core Banking module needs to call an external SaaS provider (e.g., Salesforce CRM) or a cloud-native Fraud Machine Learning Model hosted in our AWS Region West.
	•	Option A: Direct Outbound via NAT / Forward Proxy. The Mainframe calls the internet or cloud directly via standard forward proxies (e.g., Squid/Bluecoat).
	◦	Pros: Traditional, well-understood by legacy network teams.
	◦	Cons: Lacks API-level observability. The Mainframe must manage its own OAuth client credentials and token lifecycles, which is an integration nightmare for COBOL/legacy systems.
	•	Option B: Route through the DC Ingress Gateway. Use the existing Ingress Gateway for outbound traffic.
	◦	Pros: Reuses existing infrastructure.
	◦	Cons: Mixes trust zones. Ingress hardware optimized for WAF/DDoS is different from hardware optimized for outbound data loss prevention (DLP) and token caching.
	•	Option C: Dedicated DC Egress API Gateway. Establish a distinct internal Egress Gateway dedicated to outbound API calls.
	◦	Pros: The Egress Gateway handles the heavy lifting of modern authentication (e.g., executing the OAuth2 Client Credentials grant to get a JWT for AWS/SaaS) on behalf of the Mainframe. It enforces outbound rate limits and shields the legacy core from cloud timeouts via circuit breakers.
Recommendation: Option C (Dedicated DC Egress API Gateway). Rationale: We cannot expect legacy Mainframes or monolithic Core Banking systems to gracefully handle modern API security protocols, retry logic, or circuit breaking. The Egress API Gateway acts as a Sidecar/Façade for the Datacenter. The Mainframe makes a simple, unauthenticated HTTP/mTLS call to the Egress Gateway; the Egress Gateway secures the token, attaches it, routes to the cloud/SaaS, and standardizes the response. Traversal Path:Mainframe → DC Egress Gateway (acquires token) → Egress Firewall → Direct Connect / Internet → Cloud Service.
